# Bun Project Rules

## Mandatory Context

Before making any changes:

1. Read the root `README.md` ŌĆö its Documentation section lists every doc with a link and description
2. Inspect all file names under `docs/` and subfolders in the current repository ŌĆö some files may be missing from the README
3. Read files that appear relevant to the current task
4. Treat `docs/` as the source of truth for project-specific conventions and follow those documents over this file when they conflict

**Rule Markers Legend:**

- ­¤ż¢ = Automated by linter (ESLint/Stylelint enforces this)
- ­¤æż = Human-enforced (requires manual review)

## 1. Core Principles

- ­¤æż Context first: Gather complete understanding before changes
- ­¤æż Pattern matching: Check existing codebase for similar implementations
- ­¤æż Progressive enhancement: Build incrementally, test frequently
- ­¤æż Functional/declarative patterns; avoid classes
- ­¤æż Keep dependencies minimal - prefer built-in features
- ­¤æż Every line of code must be used or removed
- ­¤æż The fewer lines of code the better
- ­¤æż Avoid code duplication - maximize reuse
- ­¤æż Do not over-engineer - only make directly requested changes. No abstractions for single-use code, no unrequested configurability, no error handling for impossible scenarios. If 200 lines could be 50, rewrite
- ­¤æż Surface assumptions and ambiguities before coding; if multiple interpretations exist, present them - don't pick silently
- ­¤æż Define verifiable success criteria before implementing (test, command, or observable behavior)
- ­¤æż Every changed line must trace to the request - no opportunistic refactors of adjacent code or unrelated formatting
- ­¤æż When deleting unused code, only remove orphans your changes created; mention pre-existing dead code instead of deleting it
- ­¤æż Be consistent with existing code style
- ­¤æż Do not remove existing code/comments unless necessary
- ­¤æż Write plan before changes, not report after

## 2. Architecture

### 2.1 Technology Stack

- Bun, TypeScript 6.x
- ESLint for linting
- Prettier for formatting

### 2.2 Directory Layout

- `scripts/` - Scripts

## 3. Project Structure

### 3.1 File Organization

- ­¤æż Single module file only ŌåÆ no directory. Example: `example.ts`
- ­¤æż Multiple module files ŌåÆ create directory, NO index.ts. Example: `example/example.ts`, `example/example.test.ts`, `example/example.types.ts`, `example/example.module.css`.

### 3.2 Import Rules

- ­¤ż¢ Always import from actual files - never barrel files (`import/order`)
- ­¤ż¢ Import order: builtin ŌåÆ external ŌåÆ internal ŌåÆ parent ŌåÆ sibling
- ­¤æż No generic names (index.ts, init.ts) - use descriptive names

## 4. Naming Conventions

- ­¤ż¢ Variables/functions: camelCase (`@typescript-eslint/naming-convention`)
- ­¤ż¢ Components/types/interfaces: PascalCase
